Durban - KwaZulu-Natal police alongside Search and Rescue recovered four bodies in five days in the province. The police in KZN shared the information on most of the bodies they recovered on their Twitter page over the weekend. On Sunday morning, KZN police and divers from Durban Search and Rescue and Metro Search and Rescue were called out to recover the body of an unknown man from the uMvoti River, on the north coast of KZN. The divers recovered a decomposed body which they handed over to police and an inquest docket was opened by KwaDukuza police. On Sunday afternoon, Pietermaritzburg Search and Rescue, police divers and K9 Search and Rescue recovered the body of a 12-year-old boy who drowned at Upper Tugela, in Sandlwana at Woodstock Dam mouth. Police also opened an inquest docket. In another incident, Durban Search and Rescue police divers were called out to North Beach Pier on Thursday night where a fisherman had discovered a body. Police opened an inquest docket. On May 1, the police Search and Rescue team in Durban recovered the body of a 27-year-old man from the beach after he allegedly drowned. Point police are investigating an inquest on the incident, said Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane, police spokesperson. Daily News